snippet.textDisplay: Not really good evidence that the flu vaccine is effective (if you have such actual FACTUAL independent study showing it is, please provide it).  Last time I had the flu (proven with a nose swab - Influenza A) my symptoms were very mild, less than a common cold.  What made me think it might be flu was I briefly had a 101 temp.  My wife did the swab (she's a GP) and to her surprise it was the flu.  What I do is take Vitamin D, neti pot to reduce viral load (daily regardless, as I also have allergies), zinc and olive leaf extract when I think I've been infected, and lots of bed rest.  I have sever respiratory issues (and not young) so its important to avoid and deal with this early on.  Hospital is the last place I'd want to go, who needs to ad a super bug to the mix?  Oh, btw, my wife takes vitamin D for cold sores, works really well, when she forgets to for a long time, her cold sores come back.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thanks, Dr. Mike for helping to keep the general public informed. I'm living in Tianjin right now and it's a bit stressful but we're all doing our best to keep each other and ourselves safe. We just implemented a step tracking program where you scan QR codes to enter any public area, on top of temperature checking at supermarkets and upon returning to our communities. Everyone is wearing masks and surgical gloves, plus all surfaces are being disinfected at least daily. Finally, all public and private gatherings are being greatly discouraged, to the point where most malls here are closed as well. I'm super proud of the response to this. I've got a couple friends in Wuhan right now who are actively quarantined to their dorms with a rigorous gauntlet to go through in order to keep disease spread down. Even they are talking about some of the measures put in place and how proud they are. We have a tentative date to go back to work around mid-March for lesser infected areas and mid-April for more heavily infected areas, but it may be pushed back once more.

Anyway, just wanted to keep you updated on the struggle from our end. Thanks again, Dr. Mike.

snippet.textDisplay:
The issue and reason I have begun stockpiling water and dry foods is that we have an unreliable witness to these events. Lest we forget China is currently nominally a Communist nation; in reality it is pretty much a form of oligarchical Authoritarianism. The ruling elite in China have a vested interest in downplaying or underreporting what's happening with SARS-Cov 2.

They don't want to inspire panic in their people for good and bad reasons, the good reasons first. They much like any other country do not want riots in the streets, looting in the stores, and runs on the banks. The bad reason is that any appearance that the ruling party underestimated the virus will be seen as weakness and may inspire revolutionaries to come out of the woodwork or their places of hiding. It will also reduce China's international standing.

China has already taken much of the lessons they learned from encamping the Uighurs in their western provinces and applied the same apparatus to much of their cities. Constant surveillance and a brutal crackdown on reporting on the disease makes it so the only numbers we get are the numbers approved of by the ruling party. I understand we have to work with what's given, I also think it is wise to begin stockpiling even if all of this is going to die down in seven months. If it does then you will have a larder ready in case of a natural emergency.

Edit:Formatting and spelling.
